[[File:Tlk.JPG|thumb|Adatom according to the [[Terrace ledge kink|TLK model]].]]
An '''adatom''' is an [[atom]] that lies on a [[crystal]] surface, and can be thought of as the opposite of a surface [[vacancy (chemistry)|vacancy]]. This term is used in [[surface chemistry]] and [[epitaxy]], when describing single atoms lying on surfaces and [[surface roughness]]. The word is a [[portmanteau]] of "[[adsorption|adsorbed]] atom". A single atom, a cluster of atoms, or a molecule or [[molecular cluster|cluster of molecules]] may all be referred to by the general term "[[adparticle]]". This is often a thermodynamically unfavorable state. However, cases such as [[graphene]] may provide counter-examples.<ref>{{cite book |title=Epitaxy: Physical Principles and Technical Implementation |author1=Marian A. Herman |author2=Wolfgang Richter |author3=Helmut Sitter |publisher=Springer |year=2004 |isbn=3-540-67821-2 |page=322}}</ref>
== Applications == In 2012, scientists at the [[University of New South Wales]] were able to use [[phosphine]] to precisely, deterministically eject a single [[silicon]] atom onto a surface of [[epitaxy|epitaxial]] silicon. This resulting adatom created what is described as a [[single-atom transistor]]. Thus, inasmuch as chemical empirical formulas pinpoint the locations of branching ions that are attached to a particular molecule, the dopant of silicon based transistors and other such electronic components will have the location identified of each dopant atom or molecule, along with the associated characteristic of the device based on the named locations. Thus, the mapping of the dopant substances will give exact characteristics of any given [[semiconductor device]], once all is known.<ref>{{cite web | last1 = Fuechsle | first1 = Martin | last2 = Miwa | first2 = Jill A. | last3 = Mahapatra | first3 = Suddhasatta | last4 = Ryu | first4 = Hoon | title = A single-atom transistor | publisher = [[Nature (journal)|Nature]] | date = February 19, 2012 | url = http://www.nature.com/nnano/journal/vaop/ncurrent/full/nnano.2012.21.html#/main | accessdate = February 20, 2012 |display-authors=etal}}</ref>
