'''Damped Lyman alpha systems''' or '''Damped Lyman alpha absorption systems''' are concentrations of neutral [[hydrogen]] gas, detected in the [[Spectrum|spectra]] of [[quasar]]s. They are defined to be systems where the column density (density projected along the line of sight to the quasar) of hydrogen is larger than 2 x 10<sup>20</sup> atoms/cm<sup>2</sup>.<ref name=Coles>{{cite book |last1=Coles |first1=Peter |authorlink1=Peter Coles |last2=Lucchin |first2=Francesco |title=Cosmology: The Origin and Evolution of Cosmic Structure |edition=2nd |year=2002 |publisher=[[John Wiley & Sons]] |location=England |isbn=0-471-48909-3 |pages=430–432}}</ref><ref name=Encyclopedia>{{cite encyclopedia |last=Lanzetta |first=Kenneth M |encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Astronomy and Astrophysics |title=Lyman Alpha Absorption: The Damped Systems |year=2001 |isbn=0-333-75088-8}}</ref>
The observed spectra consist of neutral hydrogen [[Lyman alpha]] absorption lines which are broadened by [[radiation damping]]. These systems can be observed in quantity at relatively high [[redshift]]s of 2-4, when they contained most of the neutral hydrogen in the universe. They are believed to be associated with the early stages of [[Galaxy formation and evolution|galaxy formation]], as the high neutral hydrogen column densities of DLAs are also typical of sightlines in the [[Milky Way]], and other nearby galaxies. Since they are observed in absorption rather than by their stars, they offer the opportunity to study the dynamics of the gas in early galaxies directly.
==See also== *[[Lyman-alpha blob]] *[[Lyman-alpha emitter]] *[[Lyman-alpha forest]] *[[Lyman-break galaxy]]
